"12 ounce bottle into tulip glass; no bottle dating, but was released recently. Pours clear nearly opaque dark reddish brown color with a 2 finger dense and rocky khaki head with great retention, that reduces to a nice cap that lingers. Spotty soapy lacing clings around the glass, with some moderate streaming carbonation. Aromas of big grapefruit, orange zest, lemon zest, orange rind, tangerine, cocoa, chocolate, roasted malt, toast, light char, floral, grass, light pine, and floral/roasted earthiness. Very nice aromas with good balance and complexity of hop and roasted malt notes; with good strength. Taste of big grapefruit, tangerine, orange zest, lemon zest, orange rind, cocoa, roasted malt, chocolate, toast, light char, floral, grass, pine, and floral/roasted earthiness. Moderate amount of earthy pine bitterness on the finish; with lingering notes of citrus, citrus zest/rind, cocoa, roast, chocolate, toast, light char, pine, floral, and grass on the finish for a good bit. Very nice compexity and balance of hop and roasted malt flavors; with a crisp malt/bitterness balance and zero cloying flavors after the finish. Medium carbonation and body; with a moderately crisp, sticky, and slightly chalky mouthfeel that is good. Alcohol is very well hidden with minimal warming present after the finish. Overall this is a very nice Black IPA style. All around good balance and complexity of hop and roasted malt flavors; and very smooth and crisp to drink. A very enjoyable offering."
"O-First, let me say what a good-looking black ale this is! Moving on...this is a decent example of a black ale with a good balance between citrus-forward hops and dark, chocolatey malt flavors. I could use more oomph on the nose, and the feel was strange, but the flavor is pretty solid. The hops may have faded a bit in this bottle, but I still detect a decent bit of citrus up front, which provides a nice contrast the cocoa-flavored finish. Not bad."
